{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DT, top of your \DT-9 holding — a safe, passive start against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S with twenty-one points facing a weak dummy — ten tricks to find. Count the certain losers: a heart, a diamond, and the trump king somewhere. That is three, and the \CQ looms as the fourth. A club finesse is the lazy line; the craftsman's line is to LOSE your three losers early and on your terms, so that whoever wins the third one is left holding only poisoned cards. Watch how the timing does all the work.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the diamond lead in dummy. Cash the top hearts and concede the third — East wins and cashes his diamond king, your two unavoidable red losers gone early, and note dummy's queen and your jack of diamonds are now high. When East exits a trump, WEST's king takes the trick — and the position is perfect: West holds nothing but minor cards. A diamond gives your jack a trick; a club rides into your A-J. He chose the club; your JACK won on the spot, and the ace-king finished his queen. Ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The strip here wasn't a flourish — it was ordinary plays made in the RIGHT ORDER: red-suit losers conceded early, winners kept as guards, and the trump king allowed to win exactly when West had only losing exits. Rectify early, strip as you go, and the throw-in plays itself. The finesse you never took was the trick you never risked.}
