{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C4, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against the heart game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Stayman found the four-four fit and you are in 4\H needing ten. The problem suit is diamonds: K-J-8-7 in your hand, a lone six in dummy, and the ace-queen somewhere behind. That suit is FROZEN — if you touch it, the ace and queen beat your king and jack out of two tricks. But if THEY touch it, your king and jack sit over every card East can lead. So the plan writes itself: never play diamonds. Strip the clubs, strip the spades, give West the two trump tricks he owns — and leave the defenders alone on stage with the one suit nobody wanted to play.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The club lead rides to dummy's queen; cash the king. Three rounds of spades end in your hand. Trump ace, then a LOW trump — West's queen wins and his king cashes; East's ten-four fall, and the trumps are done. Now West is on lead with nothing good: a spade is a ruff-and-discard, a club runs to dummy's ace while the lead stays poisoned, so he tries the diamond two. Dummy's six forces East's ACE — beating air — and count East's hand: spades gone, hearts gone, clubs gone. Every card he holds is a diamond, and each one walks into your K-J. The jack wins, the king wins, and dummy ruffs the fourth. Ten tricks; the queen died in his hand.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] A frozen suit is a standoff: whoever opens it, loses it. The strip is how you make sure it is not you — burn their safe suits, cash their trump tricks FOR them, and the standoff ends with a defender forced to move first. Note the cascade: West's exit did not solve his problem, it handed the same problem to East, whose hand had been reduced to pure poison. When both defenders are stripped, the frozen suit thaws one forced lead at a time.}
[Note "1:Stayman"]
