{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H5, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against the spade game; dummy has shown a big raise, so passive is prudent.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] The slam try stopped in time: Blackwood found a keycard away plus the trump queen, and 5\S needs eleven. Then West's first discard on a trump will confirm the bad news — East began with ALL FOUR missing trumps, A-Q-T-5 over your J-9-6-4-3. Count his entitlements: the queen can ruff a winner, the ace is the ace, and the TEN sits behind your jack for a third. That is one trick too many. The endplay answer: strip every side suit to the bone, let him take the first two his way, and make the ten LEAD instead of lie in wait.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Dummy's bare heart ace wins. Unblock the clubs — king, then the ten covered and overtaken; East shows out and the strip begins: heart king, heart ruff, diamond ace-king with East's jack and queen crashing on air, third diamond ruffed. Nine cards gone from every hand and not a safe suit left in East's. Lead dummy's good club: East ruffs with the QUEEN — trick one, always his — and exits a heart; ruff it and accept the small ruff-and-discard toll. Now the trump king: East's ACE swallows it, trick two, the last they get. He is down to the T-5 of trumps and nothing else: the five rides around to your NINE, and your JACK collects his ten at the thirteenth trick. Eleven.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] East's trump ten was a winner by position — behind your jack, guarded by the ace-queen in front of it — and no honest play of the suit could ever catch it. So the suit was never played honestly: the strip removed his exits, the throw-in sold him the king, and position reversed itself the instant he had to LEAD. A card that wins lying fourth under cover dies leading fifth into the open. That is the deepest form of the strip: it does not just save a finesse — it turns the defenders' own trump geometry inside out.}
